    difficulty: "Beginner",
    body: "For many tribes, the elders are the last fluent speakers of the language and the keepers of stories that have never been written down. Recording those stories is one of the most important gifts an elder can give to the grandchildren and great-grandchildren who follow. The good news is that the tools to do this work are now sitting on almost every kitchen table. A smartphone, a tablet, or a basic laptop can produce recordings that sound as good as a professional studio, as long as you know which app to open and how to keep the file safe.\n\nThis guide focuses on three pieces of the task. First, picking the right device and app for your comfort level. Most elders find the Voice Memos app on an iPhone, the Recorder app on an Android phone, or the free Audacity software on a Windows or Mac laptop the right place to start. Second, choosing a quiet room and setting up the device so the recording sounds clean. Third, saving the files in multiple places so the work is not lost when a phone breaks, a hard drive crashes, or an account closes.\n\nMany tribes now run language preservation programs that will support your recordings with transcription, translation, and archival storage. The American Indian Higher Education Consortium, the Indigenous Language Institute, and many tribal colleges offer free training and equipment lending libraries. If your tribe runs a cultural center or a heritage department, call before you start because they may want to coordinate or provide a higher-quality microphone.\n\nThe most important thing is to start. A short recording made today is better than a long perfect one that never happens. Most family stories run between five and 30 minutes. Plan a few sessions rather than one long one because voices tire and quality drops after about an hour. This guide gives you the steps to record your first story this weekend, and a path to build a larger family archive over the months and years to come.",
